english:
  title: 'Epitaph for Han Gong, Lord of Hanyang: With Preface'
  author: Lee In-bok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    His name was Jong-yu, and his courtesy name was Sa-go. He was from Hanyang. At fifteen, he entered the National Academy, where he distinguished himself through diligent study, earning a reputation for excellence. Before reaching manhood, he passed the civil service examination and achieved the third rank. In the early years of Yanyou, appointed as acting inspector of collation, he was selected to serve as examiner in the Archives of Literature and the Spring-Autumn Annals. Following King Chungsuk to the Yuan court, he recorded the daily chronicles of the traveling palace and oversaw the drafting of all official documents. Upon his return to Goryeo, he was promoted to Recorder of the Bureau of Equipages with the rank of Seventh Rank Official, receiving vestments of the sixth grade. He served successively as Bureau Director and Court Draftsman, while holding concurrent posts in the Archives and Annals, and men said he was suited to his office.

    When the Zhizhi era came, slanderers attacked King Chungsuk, causing him to be summoned to the Yuan capital. As Prince Shen pressed his claim to the throne, he sent word saying, "I have already secured the position." The people of the realm grew confused. But our Lord Han alone rose with righteous indignation, determined to clear King Chungsuk's name. He joined with sixteen worthy scholars in a formal petition of several hundred words. My grandfather, the Lord of Literary Excellence, himself journeyed to the Yuan capital and presented it to the prime minister. King Chungsuk attributed much of the success to our Lord, who was elevated to Vice Minister of the Secret Secretariat.

    In the final years of the Taidng era, King Chungsuk was misled by those in power. They secretly showed him an abdication edict and instructed him to affix the seal, urging haste. Our Lord, then serving as Knowledge Officer of the Secret Secretariat, firmly remonstrated but could not move the king. Withdrawing, he feigned a fall from his horse and remained confined. With my grandfather and the great ministers, he revealed the matter to the throne. The ministers consulted with the princes and princes of the blood, seized the conspirators, and dismissed them. The matter was prevented, though our Lord lost his position as a result.

    When the first year of Zhishun arrived and King Chungye ascended, our Lord was recalled to serve as Chief Counselor of the Secret Secretariat. The following year he was promoted to Minister of the Court of Literary Deliberations and examiner of tribute scholars. The year after, when King Chungsuk resumed power, our Lord retired to his native place and built a house there. In the final years of Zhiyuan, King Chungsuk passed away, and Cao Di raised a rebellion. Our Lord returned from his retirement, and together with my grandfather and the other great ministers, attended upon King Chungye. When Cao Di was defeated, the late Prime Minister Kim Lun and our Lord investigated his followers. The case records were transmitted by relay to the Yuan, but Prime Minister Baayan failed to report them and instead summoned King Chungye to the capital. Our Lord accompanied the king. There, all were imprisoned and matters became uncertain. My grandfather sought to submit a memorial to vindicate them, but fortunately Baayan died, and their case was resolved. After King Chungye's restoration, his merits were recorded and he was appointed to the Council of Remonstrance, then advanced to Vice Premier. He was granted the title of Marquis of Demonstrated Loyalty, Preserved Integrity, and Cultivated Transformation.

    In the winter of the third year of Zhizheng, when King Chungye journeyed to the Yuan, imperial envoys appointed our Lord as an emissary of tribute. The following January, by imperial decree, he escorted King Chungmok back to Goryeo to assist in governance. Thus he was appointed Vice Premier of the Council, judge of military affairs, and senior guard, with additional enfeoffment. Soon after, he was elevated to Lord of Hanyang.

    In his official posts, he rose from Examiner and Editor through the two archives to become Chief Counselor of the Departments of Literature and the Archives, serving as supervisor of the Spring-Autumn Annals. In rank, he rose nine times from Seventh Rank Official to the highest honors. After retiring from office and returning to his native place, he rarely visited the capital unless official duties called. Before the present king ascended the throne, the elder statesmen looked to him with hope, and he was among them. The king thereafter showed him exceptional courtesy whenever they met.

    In the summer of the fourteenth year of Zhizheng, on the day wuxu of the sixth month, he passed away from illness at his old residence in the capital. As his condition became critical, he addressed his sons and sons-in-law, saying: "I rose from humble cloth garments and received the state's abundant favor, attaining the highest ranks. Though I have not reached full span of years, what regret remains? Three days hence, I shall bid you farewell. Await that time." True to his word, three days later he departed. All who heard of his death, far and near, wept together in condolence, saying, "Alas, our great minister has gone." The king suspended his court audiences and had officials conduct the funeral rites. He was posthumously named Wen-jie, the Cultured Resolute One. In the eighth month on the day renyin, he was buried at the southern slope of the Seonjak Temple on Daedeok Mountain. He lived to sixty-eight years.

    His great-grandfather was named Yuan-seo, who attained the posthumous rank of Vice Minister of State Affairs. His grandfather was named Eon, who became Eastern Regional Inspector of Officials and received posthumous appointment as Coadjutor of the Secret Secretariat. His father was named Young, Vice Minister of the Secret Secretariat and Senior Guard, retired. His mother was Lady Yi, Dame of Haman County.

    Our Lord's bearing differed from ordinary men—his appearance was striking and his frame imposing, such that one could perceive him destined for the highest offices. Before his advancement, he moved among the renowned scholars of the time, gathering daily over wine. When drunk, he would rise, sweep his sleeves, and dance while singing "The Song of Willow Blossoms": "Awaiting the moon-dark and crystalline wind, I soar and alight in the Yellow Hall of State." Discerning men marked this as extraordinary. From his position as examiner to his role as prime minister, he always oversaw the selection and promotion of officials, and many relatives and friends achieved advancement through his aid. His nature was generous and weighty; in handling affairs and meeting people, he ever maintained composure. In composition, he strove to escape worldly vulgarity, and he devoted particular attention to poetry. He loved witty discourse, and in convivial gatherings, a genial warmth would naturally flow forth, endearing him to all. He styled himself "Fu-zhai," the Studio of Return.

    In his youth, Lord Yi, Minister of State, saw him once at the National Academy and forthwith betrothed him to the daughter of his son, the Lord of Garak, named Guan. He fathered three sons—Bo-chun, Jung-myeong, and Gae-sang—and five daughters.

    At the time of the funeral, his sons consulted together, saying: "Among those who worked closely with our father, only Lord Li, the Cultured Exemplar, knew him most fully. His grandson In-bok served both elders, has witnessed much, and is now a historian. He is able to recount our father's deeds and transmit them endlessly to posterity." Thus they came to commission this epitaph.

    The epitaph reads:

    A vessel spacious and great,
    Learning broad, his name established—
    Wherever employed, all flourished.
    Three monarchs he served in succession,
    With loyalty and diligence constant,
    His official seal bore the mark of high station.
    He kindled blessings from his own person,
    Beginning well and ending well—
    Such was the radiance of his virtue.
    This stone we bury in the grave,
    This writing my brush has traced;
    Let future generations not forget.
  footnotes:
    - 'Yanyou (延祐): The era name during the Yuan Dynasty (1314-1320).'
    - 'Yi-ling (毅陵): The posthumous temple name of King Chungsuk of Goryeo.'
    - 'Shen Wang (瀋王): Crown Prince of the Yuan Dynasty who attempted to usurp the Goryeo throne.'
    - 'The Song of Willow Blossoms (楊花詞): A poetic composition expressing lofty aspirations, with imagery suggesting elevation to high office (the Yellow Hall representing the imperial government).'
    - 'Fu-zhai (復齋): Literally "Studio of Return," his personal literary name.'
    - 'Chungye (忠惠王) and Chungsuk (忠肅王): Names of successive Goryeo kings.'
    - The historical context involves the complex politics of the Yuan Dynasty's rule over Goryeo and court factionalism in both realms.
